<div id="outline-container-org20f8801" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org20f8801">Vim and Zettelkasten</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org20f8801">
<p>
Maintaining a repository of thoughts is not a new idea. A plethora of
note-taking tools exist today, such as <a href="https://obsidian.md/">Obsidian</a>,
<a href="https://www.remnote.com/">RemNote</a> and <a href="https://roamresearch.com/">Roam
Research</a>, all of which seem inspired by the
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zettelkasten">Zettelkasten method</a>. The
technique, developed by the Swiss physician Conrad Gessner, helps its users
collate personal knowledge via numbered cards and tags. <a href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/How-Take-Smart-Notes-Nonfiction-ebook/dp/B06WVYW33Y">How to Take Smart Notes</a> provides great insight into the approach. 
</p>

<p>
Whilst I don't doubt the usefulness of the aforementioned apps, they fail to
engage me. This is because the simplicity of the Zettelkasten is what attracted
me in the first place. There is a definite serenity to benefit from, and
friction is eliminated because there are no abstractions, UIs or complex
knowledge graphs to distract. It's just you, the pen and the paper.
</p>

<p>
The only app I came close to using is "The Archive". Unlike most other tools,
it very clearly attributes its founding premise to the Zettelkasten, and its creators,
Christian and Sascha, are also authors of <a href="https://zettelkasten.de">https://zettelkasten.de</a>, a site
dedicated to the technique. If I weren't a programmer, this would unequivocally
be my tool of choice, and I highly recommend you give its 60 day trial a shot.
</p>

<p>
After using "The Archive" for a couple of days, I couldn't help but wonder: can
I replicate this process in Vim? I knew it was possible, but how much
configuration would it take? It turns out just one line.
</p>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgc442d95" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgc442d95">Why it works</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgc442d95">
<p>
What would this solution require to be effective? These were my requirements:
</p>

<ul class="org-ul">
<li>Basic editor (obviously)</li>
<li>Version control</li>
<li>Search</li>
<li>Unique note identifiers</li>
<li>Bi-directional linking</li>
<li>Dates and timestamps</li>
<li>Index files</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org4414c1a" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org4414c1a">Editor</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-org4414c1a">
<p>
If you haven't guessed, the editor is Vim. If you are a programmer, writer, or
avid typist, I definitely suggest checking it out. It has dramatically improved
my editing speed and workflow.
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org206c9df" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org206c9df">Version control</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-org206c9df">
<p>
For version control I use Git. Nothing special or surprising here. In addition
to version control, Git provides a backup of my notes, and a method of quick
retrieval should I be using other machines.
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgfad7474" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orgfad7474">Search</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-orgfad7474">
<p>
Git provides a convenient command, <code>git grep</code> which allows you to search for
patterns across a repository. Here is an example inside my  Zettelkasten:
</p>

<p>
<a href="https://asciinema.org/a/XltksfZdpGgbmzYu45EoPBk6q">https://asciinema.org/a/XltksfZdpGgbmzYu45EoPBk6q</a>
</p>

<p>
In the clip I search for the term "honours", and two files are returned: 
</p>

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>1642627149 Polygot computing.txt</code></li>
<li><code>1642661741 Page audio widget.txt</code></li>
</ul>

<p>
Both of these notes contain a reference to the <code>1642801264 Honours.txt</code> index
file. More on index files later.
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org9d65a27" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org9d65a27">Unique idenitifiers</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-org9d65a27">
<p>
You may have noticed the seemingly random set of numbers prefixing each
filename. In reality, they are not random at all, and serve an important
purpose. These numbers are Unix timestamps. Not only does this ensure every
note is unique, it also provides a way of dating thoughts. For example, the id
for the file <code>1642627149 Polygot computing.txt</code> is <code>1642627149</code>, which in GMT
resolves to <code>Wednesday, 19 January 2022 21:19:09</code>.
</p>

<p>
Here is how I register new notes:
</p>

<p>
Since all notes are unique, tab can be used to quickly autocomplete the
filename given any id:
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org94de9d1" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="org94de9d1">Bi-directional linking</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-org94de9d1">
<p>
Jumping to another file path is possible by selecting it in visual mode and
hitting <code>gf</code>. You can then navigate backwards using using <code>CTRL + o</code>.
</p>

<p>
Since the unix timestamps are difficult to recall from memory, here we find the
single line of vimscript mentioned at the beginning of the post: 
</p>

<p>
<code>nnoremap cp :let @" = expand("%:t")&lt;cr&gt;</code>
</p>

<p>
When <code>cp</code> is pressed, it conveniently copies the open filename to the
clipboard. It can then be pasted into another note to create a bi-directional
link:
</p>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orge513888" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="orge513888">Index files</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-orge513888">
<p>
A feature of Gessner's Zettelkasten are index files. If it is not clear from the
name, index files act as entry points for particular topics. This is a good way
to:
</p>

<ol class="org-ol">
<li>Identify links between existing notes and new notes</li>
<li>Retrieve all notes on a specific subject</li>
</ol>

<p>
I tend to prefer keeping the titles broad, such as "productivity", "physics" or
"CS". 
</p>

<hr />

<p>
<a href="index.html">Back</a>
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
